ployees based on individual&#10; and team achievements.&#10;&#10;Rule 2: The criteria for performance evaluations and associated benefits will be transparent and &#10;communicated in advance.&#10; Educational Assistance:&#10;&#10;Rule 1: The company may offer educational assistance programs to support employees in their&#10; professional development.&#10;&#10;Rule 2: Eligible educational expenses, application procedures, and any reimbursement limits will be&#10; clearly outlined in the benefits policy.&#10;&#10;Wellness Programs:&#10;&#10;Rule 1: The company may implement wellness programs to promote employee health and well-being.&#10;&#10;&#10;Rule 2: Wellness initiatives may include fitness classes, health screenings, mental health resources,&#10; and other wellness-related activities.&#10;&#10;Rule 3: Employees actively participating in wellness programs may be eligible for incentives or &#10;rewards.&#10;&#10;Communication of Benefits:&#10;&#10;Rule 1: Regular communication channels, such as company newsletters or intranet updates, will be&#10; utilized to inform employees about changes or updates to benefits.&#10;&#10;Rule 2: The HR department will conduct periodic benefits workshops to address employee questions &#10;and concerns.&#10;&#10; Benefits Enrollment and Changes:&#10;&#10;Rule 1: Employees will be provided with clear instructions on benefits enrollment procedures, i&#10;ncluding deadlines and required documentation.&#10;&#10;Rule 2: Changes to benefits, such as life events or changes in family status, will be communicated &#10;promptly, and employees will be guided on the necessary steps to update their benefits.&#10;&#10;Confidentiality of Benefits Information:&#10;&#10;Rule 1: Employee benefits information, including health records and enrollment details, will be&#10; treated with the utmost confidentiality.&#10;&#10;Rule 2: Access to benefits information will be restricted to authorized personnel involved in benefits&#10; administration." />
